<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Weekend of Tournaments in GA: July 12-14<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149'>Drew "Player27" Lichtenstein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 14, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> I&#8217;m a really bad player. For many months now, I&#8217;ve been working on decks, writing articles for DeckTech, and purchasing singles and boxes to perfect my craft. However, the reality of the situation is I just suck. I&#8217;ve had very little playing experience outside of about two tournaments and a handful of leagues. Whoever says this game is all deck building and skill is&#8230; partially right. However, there&#8217;s still a lot for me to learn. I do have confidence, however, that I will learn (eventually). I thought this weekend though, which featured a tournament a day between Friday and Sunday would be a perfect opportunity to enhance my playing abilities. I also think it&#8217;s important to keep tourney reports so I can at least remember details so I won&#8217;t make the same mistakes again.<br />
<br />
FRIDAY NIGHT: TOURNAMENT #1: COLOSSAL GAMES<br />
<br />
For the last couple of weeks, I&#8217;d been talking on AOL Instant Messenger with Mike Kessling. A great player, he&#8217;d offer me some sound advice on how to make my deck stronger and better. Inadvertently, I had mentioned to him this Friday was a tournament for a box of Realms over at a store called Colossal. He mentioned to me that he, Andrew Morris (another good player and a friend of mine from the glory day of Star Wars), Josh Morris (Andrew&#8217;s little brother), Clint Hayes, and Clay Ramey were also coming up. Figuring myself to already be screwed, I thought I&#8217;d try a new deck for myself. I built the concept on getting out Elf allies early on with Forests of Lothlorien and pumped up Aragorns and Boromirs to help me double move. Horn of Boromir would (in theory) make up for a smaller number of companions.<br />
<br />
Colossal is a place where I normally play leagues on Friday, so I show up a bit early and chat a bit with the local ambassador, Bill Kenyon. Bill is a nice guy -- always traveling around to run tournament, a play tester, and always has an odd or different deck. After testing a bit against his Shire/Gandalf deck, I realized that the four Hobbit start (guaranteeing me to go first) and Uruks were the way to go. While I only had the funds for one box of Realms, Uruks&#8217;s ability to be fierce and damage +1 are just too much to pass up, especially since I was running; I figured if I could slow them down, I&#8217;d be doing good enough. As soon as Mike, Andrew, Clint, and the rest of their crowd arrived, we started.<br />
<br />
Game #1 vs. Local Player Who&#8217;s Name I Always Forget.<br />
<br />
Lesson #1: Never be too pipeweedy in a game. <br />
<br />
On a normal Friday, I&#8217;d play this fellar and beat him fairly easily. He&#8217;s a nice guy, but just learning at the game. However, my deck simply fell apart on me and he was able to just drop Uruk after Uruk on me. A major death blow was his not playing anything at site two or three. Getting confident, I drop Aragron and Boromir and move&#8230; into an Enquea. I&#8217;ve realized that if I&#8217;m gonna over six to go all the way and go big. It was down hill from there and I lost Aragorn at site five to more Uruks. I had him down to just Frodo, but it wasn&#8217;t enough since he had me at the same&#8230; and less.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
I give the kid credit. I was too confident in my abilities and he really took me by surprise.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
Mainly to me. I got real mad after the game at this new player and smoked afterwards to relieve some anger. I normally never smoke a whole cigarette, or even at all, but I was mad. (And thanks to Mike for obliging me.)<br />
<br />
Game #2 vs. Trevor McGregor<br />
<br />
Lesson #2: If not using counters for discard, at least have the common sense to run more than sixty cards.<br />
<br />
At first, I didn&#8217;t really like Trevor. I have a habit of cussing like a sailor, but I&#8217;m not use to people berating me for it. However, as we played, I liked him a lot more. A nice guy using a fairly annoying deck: Mirror with Uruk discard (no White Arrows). I had him slowed down quite a bit and the deck was actually working with me having three Forests and Calagin out by site three or four. Saruman never lived past the regroup phase and I was at seven as he was chugging along at six. However, during the whole game he had been using Uruk Solider, Rager, and Mirror to get me down to only a hand of cards when he was at six -- a death blow with Gift of Boats out and him Stinging to only see two minions.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
Trevor is a nice guy who I think I&#8217;ll get to see a lot more of as I try to keep getting better. Also, I had the great joy of really annoying Clay Ramey during this game (I&#8217;m honestly not sure if he despises me or not&#8230;).<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
Me thinking &#8220;Hey, it&#8217;s a local. No one good will be here. Why worry about Mirror?&#8221; even when I knew good players would be here.<br />
<br />
Games #3 vs. Robert Morea<br />
<br />
Lesson #3: Use more than six companions.<br />
<br />
After Game #2, I got outside, take a break, get made fun of for being Jewish by Clint and Mike (though I know they&#8216;re kidding now), and trudge in for my next loss. Robert is an extremely nice guy, my ride for both that day and the next day&#8217;s tourney. His claim to fame is a Moria/Twilight Denial combo. The game was over just about as quick as it started: I hadn&#8217;t drawn one of my four Aragorn/Boromirs (two of each) by site five. With no other support for my Hobbits beside Sting, Filibert, And Thrarin (and Pippin already dead at site three), that&#8217;s game.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
Robert&#8217;s an awesome guy.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
Time to dismantle this deck. Now.<br />
<br />
After a long break talking with Andrew Morris (I lost quick and he won faster), he gives me tips for the mini-DPC tomorrow, where Mirror/White Arrows will be prominent. He suggests big Fellowship with Moria as the side culture and to make sure to include in 4 Goblin Scramblers, 2 They Are Comings, and 2 Host of Thousands to stop White Arrows and Gift of Boats. I intentionally bomb my last two games in good ol&#8217; fun fashion (feeding Frodo to Cave Troll, bidding nine and corrupting, etc&#8230;) so I can pick up a last place pack. Clint Hayes wins the tournament and I head home, watch &#8220;Farscape&#8221;, eat, and make the deck that Andrew suggested.<br />
<br />
SATURDAY: TOURNAMENT #2: T AND T TOYS<br />
<br />
I wake up early so I can tape &#8220;Mystery Science Theater 3000&#8221; (stupid VCR only tapes when the TV is actually on with the show) and then go over to meet Robert for a ride to T and T. We stop for breakfast and make it in time for the tourney, which costs $10 ($20 for me, since I have to cover Josh Morris who convientnetly has no cash on him). Deck is basically two of each big companion and one of their weapons and the Moria with anti-discard stuff.<br />
<br />
Game #1 vs. Dan Schwartz <br />
<br />
Dan is a player, like me, also learning the game. His big mistake, however, was hoping that his bid of three would be a enough to land him his Prancing Pony and Aragorn, which there was only one of in the deck. After I bid seven and use Hobbiton Woods, he was in deep trouble. He move onto the Bridge with only Arwen/Legolas&#8230; and was promptly beaten by a Scavengers and a Balrog.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
Another really nice guy. He was very pleasant the entire time and I could tell his main problem was just a lack of cards and not skill.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
Ending early and having to wait around. We did have time to play another pick up game, though.<br />
<br />
Game #2 vs. Adam Drake<br />
<br />
Adam is another guy who I know from when I use to play Star Wars (our good story is he once accidentally kicked me in the face&#8230; and I proceeded to win the tournament). He was using Mirror discard with Isengard Orcs. My deck was working quite fine&#8230; I slowed him down by making him lose White Arrows and Shoulder and was beating him at site five&#8230; when he proceeded to make my eight companions become two with the crazy that is Isengard Orcs and The Trees Are Strong. Four Orcs at each site with Coming For The Ring/Trees was enough to do me away. I moved onto to site eight with just Frodo, having lost the full eight between then.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
I may have to consider Isengard Orcs now&#8230; <br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
Being anti-discard for Shadow does nothing if their Shadow still beats you down.<br />
<br />
I go outside and hang out with a clearly depressed Clay Ramey, who is also 0-2 now with a Bill Ferny deck he is really trying to make work. I let him make fun of me and Charlie Herren comes outside and basically cheers us both up (seeing as we both really suck -- while me, anyways, Clay is normally much better).<br />
<br />
Game #3 vs. Charlie Herren<br />
<br />
I&#8217;ve never beaten Charlie in any game or anything. This was no different at all. He was running heavy twilight denial with the new Aragorn and Moria for shadow. I was unable to touch his Shadow, but my Fellowship was chugging along. I was doing real well until I hit the Bridge -- my seven companions became only Gandalf, Boromir, and Frodo after Enquea, who killed an exhausted Legolas and Sam, and a Balrog came down (I&#8217;ve now learned to not add shadow at site four). Embarrassingly, Frodo was overwhelmed at site six by two Goblin Scramblers (one with a Scimitar) proving to me that I need more Stings in my deck.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
Playing Charlie is always a hoot.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
I got mad again since I was close to winning or at least doing better the game (I had two more companions coming up in the next four cards).<br />
<br />
The rest of the tourney was fairly bland. I lost the next game to Uruks with Aragorn and Boromir showing up later (but their weapons opening hand). Won the next against another player who relied on the Pony to pull Aragorn and failed to and lost to another Moria (Lesson #4: ADD CONDITION REMOVAL ASAP). After watching Munchkin Chicknas get stung by wasps (and paying her a $1 -- I felt bad for her between my laughs), Robert and I headed home. We stopped for pizza were we tweaked our decks for tomorrow&#8217;s last tournament. I head home and play poker for the rest of the evening with some friends (another game I really need to get a bit better at) and stay up until 2 AM working on another new deck. I use the same big fellowship but trim it down to sixty cards. I go back to Uruks and use 3 Tower Assassins and 3 No Business of Ours for Mirror.<br />
<br />
SUNDAY: TOURNAMENT #3: DR. NO&#8217;S<br />
<br />
Dr. No&#8217;s doesn&#8217;t have as tough the competition as T and T normally does, but I know the guys here much better and they&#8217;re my good friends from when I use to play Star Trek here (Wars, Trek, Rings&#8230; call me a Decipher poster boy). However, Ken Brune, Trevor McGregor, and (in the nick of time) Robert show up to spice up the competition. It&#8217;s a double elimination tournament -- first one I&#8217;ve played in before.<br />
<br />
Game #1 vs. The Bye.<br />
<br />
How strange is it that in double elimination for there to be twelve people and there still be a bye. I guess for the brackets to be even you need sixteen. By luck, both Robert and Trevor (and a decent local player) got the bye, so nothing gained there.<br />
<br />
Game #2 vs. Nick Brown<br />
<br />
Nick is a great player from Star Trek and not bad at Lord of the Rings. He&#8217;s running Dwarves/Uruk-Hai, but a four Hobbit start gets me up and running and I&#8217;m two sites ahead of him for most of the game. I have eight companions moving into site eight when I hit four Uruks, Saruman, and Brown Lands. I take six archery and precede to lose four companions between that blood bath and the skirmishes. However, his draw had been very heavy on the shadow side early in the game and he can only follow that up with an Orphan Assassin when I move to site nine the next turn.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
I think I&#8217;ve finally gotten the right combination for this deck down. An Uruk shadow site (with splashes of Cantea/Enquea/Tower Assassins) and a big fellowship with their toys (two Stings included) trimmed down to sixty cards works like a charm.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
The game was fairly on sided, but it wasn&#8217;t his deck issue: he just couldn&#8217;t get fellowship.<br />
<br />
Game #3 vs. Trevor McGregor<br />
<br />
OK, my deck is better and I&#8217;m finally packing some Mirror counters. The net result is probably the closest game I&#8217;ve played of Lord of the Rings. I got first, squeak my way into site three using Buckleberry Ferry as cover (I love the four Hobbit start), but am slightly marred by six shadow cards opening hand (only an Armor and Ranger&#8216;s Sword for fellowship). He drops an Aragorn, Elrond, Arwen, and Sam opening hand and I take advantage of that Shadow by dropping an Enquea and an Uruk Captain with two Savageries on him at site two. The Enquea drops Legolas and the seventeen strength Captain kills Arwen (Aragorn&#8217;s Sword saves him the first time around). Outside of an early turn Pippin, I lose no one else until site nine, even after another site eight with Saruman and many friends. He sets up Mirror after Secret Sentiling away my No Business of Ours&#8230; and fails to get Tower Assassin. I stop Galadirel, however, his fellowship was already badly hurt from the site two beating that it really came down to my site nine. I had eight companions (many with weapons) going into it and loads and loads of twilight (having played Sleep early to clear out No Business so I could Sting). I hit the Summit of Uruk-Hais Cost Minus One and face:<br />
Ulaire Nereta, Saruman, Uruk Captain, Uruk, Warrior, Uruk Raider (with Thrarin, Filibert, and Elrond in dead pile from various Tower Assassins), Uruk Guard, Lurtz, and Uruk Solider. However, Legolas is able to archery away Nereta, Gimli takes one (saved by Saruman), Gandalf another, and Aragorn becomes defender +3 and takes four. The net result leaves him with six fierce minions at site nine to my seven companions.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
My closest game in a very long time. Finally beating a decent player (outside of a fluke win against Andrew Morris once). The deck working the way it should have.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
Trevor is a great player and I finally realized that luck is a huge issue in this game: my opening hand with a Captain, Enquea, and two Savageries made the game entirely his Shadow vs. my Fellowship.<br />
<br />
Game #4 vs. Robert Morea<br />
<br />
Well, had to happen at some point. Seeing as he help tweaked each other&#8217;s decks, there was no surprise of what we were playing. The fault was in mine: I double moved too rarely (only once against 1-3) when I should have realized that I was in trouble if I didn&#8217;t. He had all four Armories by site three and I didn&#8217;t pull my Sleep until site eight. Coupled in with the fact he was running solid denial (never more than two Uruks a site) and many a Frodo pumpers and I sat back as he took the cake walk to site nine.<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
Playing Robert is always fun. We basically played with our hand face up (&#8220;Look, this card you said I should use is great!&#8221; or &#8220;Man, you&#8217;re an idiot!&#8221;).<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
I should have been more gutsy in my double moves.<br />
<br />
Because of the double elimination format, Robert is definitely in the final bracket and I have to wait around for two more games. During this time, Trevor takes his second loss and is eliminated. In the end, Mike Brown (our TD/Ambassador and another friend of mine from Trek) is my opponent. The winner (both of us with one loss) faces Robert and will have to beat him twice to win it all.<br />
<br />
Then the store closes. Since double elimination takes so long, we went way over time. So, this Tuesday evening me and Mike will play and then the winner will take on Robert for the winner of tournament.<br />
<br />
PROPS FOR THE WEEKEND:<br />
<br />
I think I&#8217;m finally getting better. I noticed a major improvement from Friday to Sunday in my decks and how they were played. I have a very long way to go, of course, but a penny a day&#8230;<br />
<br />
Robert is extremely awesome. He helped me with decks and drove me long distances the whole weekend. If I have to ride with someone, I can&#8217;t imagine someone nicer.<br />
<br />
Andrew Morris is still the coolest person I know.<br />
<br />
Mike Kessling for helping me with decks.<br />
<br />
Clint Hayes for not ripping my throat out.<br />
<br />
I bugged Clay Ramey enough on Friday night to cause him to push me out of my chair. Man, I need to write an entire tournament report each week and keep score of how much I annoy the shimmer out of him. Stay tuned&#8230; <br />
<br />
SLOPS FOR THE WEEKEND:<br />
<br />
The &#8220;inner group&#8221; of Charlie, Clay, Adam, Clint, Mike, (and to a *much* lesser extent Andrew and Josh). I dunno, I just feel like they&#8217;ll never respect me until I win. Always getting made of fun and never taken seriously, even when I know they&#8217;re just kidding, does weacloberrson down after two days straight.<br />
<br />
Losing money in poker. Take my word for it: never, ever play two straight games of Indian. No one has that much luck.<br />
<br />
Peace,<br />
Drew<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
